Gobest Cab Sprint 2 (CA2): ML Model for Trip Safety Prediction

Role: Person A (ML Engineer)
Goal: Train a machine learning model to classify trips as Safe (0) or Dangerous (1) using sensor data.

Deliverables for Sprint 2:

  1. ML-focused EDA
  2. Advanced Feature Engineering (10 new features, no leakage)
  3. Model training + evaluation (and later deployment integration)
  4. Track experiments (e.g., MLflow)

Recap: What was completed in Sprint 1 (CA1)`

Sprint 1 focused on building a data foundation and dashboards for business stakeholders.

Sprint 1 objective (descriptive analytics)
  • Ingest historical data into SQL
  • Perform initial EDA + cleaning
  • Engineer interpretable features for dashboards
  • Build interactive dashboards to answer user stories (CEO / analyst / customer)
Sprint 1 datasets and outcomes
  • sensor_dataset (per second, per trip): cleaned/imputed, flags created to preserve traceability
  • driver_df: added driver age, basic enrichment
  • safety_status: trip label table (bookingID, driver_id, label)
  • Output: a trip-level feature table for dashboards (avg/max speed, event counts, risk score, etc.)
Sprint 2 problem framing: What type of ML task is this?`

This is a supervised binary classification problem.

  • Target (y): label (0 = safe, 1 = dangerous)
  • Prediction unit: one prediction per trip (bookingID)
  • Although the sensor readings are time-ordered (time-series per trip), we are not forecasting future sensor values.
  • Instead, we perform time-series feature extraction to convert each trip into a set of predictive features, then train a classifier.
Data flow (high level)

Time-series sensor readings (per second, per trip)
Feature engineering (temporal patterns: volatility, extremes, burstiness, rolling stats)
Trip-level feature table (one row per trip)
Binary classification model
Predict trip safety (0/1)

Aspect Sprint 1 (Dashboard Features) Sprint 2 (ML Prediction Features)
Goal Summarize trips for visualization Predict future dangerous behavior
Audience CEO, Safety Officer (humans reading dashboards) Machine Learning model
Granularity Trip-level aggregations only Trip-level + temporal patterns + interactions
Focus "What happened?" (descriptive) "What patterns predict danger?" (predictive)
Features Simple sums, averages, counts Rolling windows, variance, interactions, ratios
Example harsh_brake_count = 5 harsh_brake_intensity_variance, harsh_brake_clustering_score

Key design principles (how features are chosen)

Sprint 2 feature engineering is prediction-driven, not dashboard-driven.

Sprint 1 vs Sprint 2 feature engineering contrast

  • Sprint 1 (descriptive): create features that are simple + interpretable for dashboards (mean, max, count)
  • Sprint 2 (predictive): create features that help a model learn patterns (volatility, percentiles, rolling windows, event clustering, interactions)

Principles used to design features

  1. Domain logic: Dangerous driving is often sudden and erratic
    (e.g., harsh braking bursts, sharp turns, high-speed maneuvers)
  2. EDA-guided: We create features that reflect patterns observed between safe vs dangerous trips
  3. Prediction-time constraint: Features must be computable from data available up to that time (no future knowledge)
  4. No label leakage: Features must not use the target and must not act as a proxy for how the label was created

Preventing data leakage (critical)

We distinguish between:

  • Valid predictive features: derived only from sensor/driver inputs
  • Leakage / proxy features: features that may directly replicate the rule used to generate label

Known proxy-risk features from Sprint 1 In Sprint 1, we created trip_risk_score and trip_safety_score using a hand-crafted scoring rule based on harsh events. Because the dataset label may be derived using similar rules, these features can become label leakage by proxy.

Decision:

  • Keep trip_risk_score / trip_safety_score for EDA interpretation only
  • Drop them from model training features

Sprint 2 workflow plan (step-by-step)

Already completed in Sprint 1:

  • Sensor-level cleaning + imputation + flags

Sprint 2 steps:

  1. ML-focused EDA

    • class imbalance
    • feature vs target comparison
    • temporal differences by class
    • leakage checks

  2. Data preparation for feature computation

    • ensure sorting by (bookingID, second)
    • verify time continuity
    • handle NaNs that break rolling operations

  3. Advanced feature engineering (10 new features)

    • Rolling-window burst features
    • Distribution features (p95/p99, std, range)
    • Burstiness features (max consecutive risky seconds)
    • Interaction/context features (speed turns, speed braking)
    • Sensor quality features (low GPS %, missingness %)

  4. Model-level preprocessing

    • train-test split strategy
    • scaling (only when needed, depending on model)
    • remove identifiers / leakage-risk columns

  5. Handle class imbalance

    • choose between SMOTE, under-sampling, or class weights

  6. Train + evaluate model

    • metrics: precision/recall/F1, ROC-AUC, confusion matrix
    • interpret feature importance
    • log experiments (MLflow)

Data used in Sprint 2

  • sensor_dataset_cleaned: per-second sensor readings + cleaning flags
  • driver_df: driver metadata (including engineered age)
  • safety_status: trip labels (bookingID, driver_id, label)

Key identifier used throughout: bookingID

EDA Strategy for Sprint 2 (ML Development)

We perform EDA in two layers:

Phase 1 Light dataset sanity checks (quality assurance)

Purpose: Confirm the Sprint 1 cleaned datasets are consistent and mergeable.

  • Check shapes, datatypes, key uniqueness
  • Check missingness summary (only key columns)
  • Check whether keys match across tables (orphan bookingIDs/driverIDs)
Phase 2 Deep ML-focused EDA (target-driven)

Purpose: Identify patterns that help predict label and inform feature engineering. We structure the analysis as:

  1. Target analysis (class imbalance, baseline accuracy)
  2. Numerical features vs target (distribution overlap, effect sizes)
  3. Identifier-based patterns (driver-level stats for understanding, not direct model input)
  4. Correlation & redundancy (multicollinearity)
  5. Temporal characteristics (volatility, extremes, burstiness, rolling-window behaviour)
  6. Data quality by class (GPS quality, missingness vs label)
  7. Leakage checks (proxy features such as risk_score)

Important methodology:

  • Because multiple trips belong to the same driver, model evaluation will use driver-based grouping to reduce identity leakage.

3. DEEP ML-FOCUSED EDA

Structure: Numerical Categorical Target Relationships

Why ML-Focused EDA is required in Sprint 2?

In Sprint 1, EDA was descriptive and business-oriented, focusing on understanding the dataset and supporting dashboard design.

In Sprint 2, EDA becomes predictive and model-driven.

The goal of ML-focused EDA is to:

  • Understand the difficulty of the prediction task

  • Identify patterns that differentiate safe vs dangerous trips

  • Detect data imbalance, noise, and leakage risks

  • Inform feature engineering, preprocessing, and model selection

Creation of EDA-only helper columns:

  • These are temporary helper columns that help observe behavioural differences between safe and dangerous trips.

  • These constructs are used purely for analytical understanding and should not be confused with final engineered features used for model training.

In[19]:
# EDA helper thresholds (can tune later)
SPEEDING_THRESHOLD = 25.0          # m/s  90 km/h
HARSH_BRAKE_THRESHOLD = -3.0       # m/s^2
HARSH_ACCEL_THRESHOLD = 3.0        # m/s^2
SHARP_TURN_THRESHOLD = 0.25        # rad/s (using gyro_z abs as a proxy)

# Longitudinal acceleration based on Speed differences
df_copy['delta_speed'] = df_copy.groupby('bookingID')['Speed'].diff()
df_copy['delta_time']  = df_copy.groupby('bookingID')['second'].diff()

df_copy['longitudinal_acc'] = df_copy['delta_speed'] / df_copy['delta_time']
df_copy.loc[~np.isfinite(df_copy['longitudinal_acc']), 'longitudinal_acc'] = np.nan

# Event flags (EDA-only)
df_copy['is_speeding'] = (df_copy['Speed'] > SPEEDING_THRESHOLD).astype(int)
df_copy['is_harsh_braking'] = (df_copy['longitudinal_acc'] <= HARSH_BRAKE_THRESHOLD).astype(int)
df_copy['is_harsh_acceleration'] = (df_copy['longitudinal_acc'] >= HARSH_ACCEL_THRESHOLD).astype(int)
df_copy['is_sharp_turn'] = (df_copy['gyro_z'].abs() >= SHARP_TURN_THRESHOLD).astype(int)

The thresholds used in this analysis are heuristic and domain-informed rather than absolute definitions of dangerous driving. Driving risk is inherently context-dependent (e.g., road type, traffic conditions), which is not fully observable in the dataset. Therefore, these thresholds are used only as exploratory indicators to study behavioural patterns, not as definitive rules for classification

Step 1: Target Variable Analysis

We have to understand the preditcion task (target)

Why class imbalance matters?

If one class dominates (e.g. 90% safe, 10% dangerous):

  • A nave model can achieve 90% accuracy by predicting safe all the time. This makes the model biased towards MAJORITY class

  • Minority class may be poorly learnt

  • Accuracy becomes misleading metric

Whether to apply SMOTE, class weighting, or other imbalance handling techniques

Baseline accuracy:  75.03%

Observations

  • The dataset consists of 75.04% safe trips (Label 0) and 24.96% dangerous trips (Label 1) which is clearly imbalanced

  • While not "extreme" (like fraud detection where the minority is often <1%), this 3:1 ratio means the model will naturally be biased toward the safe class. We will likely need to use Weighted Loss Functions or SMOTE to ensure the model doesn't ignore the dangerous drivers.

Step 2: Numerical Features Analysis (By Target)

Don't analyze numericals in isolation, we should always split by target!

2.1 Trip-level dataset

Why we aggregate to trip level?

  • Although the raw sensor data is recorded per second, the prediction task is per trip.Therefore:

    • Feature analysis must be done at the same granularity as prediction

    • One row = one bookingID = one label

  • If we analyze per-second data directly, we would:

    • Artificially inflate the dataset

    • Over-represent long trips

    • Violate the modelling assumption of independent samples

Interpretation of key aggregated features

Each aggregated feature represents a behavioural signal:

  • Speed_mean, Speed_max, Speed_std

    • Average behaviour, extremes, and variability of speed

  • longitudinal_acc_*

    • Intensity and volatility of acceleration/braking

  • gyro_z_*

    • Turning behaviour and steering aggressiveness

  • Event counts (is_speeding_sum, etc.)

    • Frequency of risky behaviours within a trip

  • Data quality metrics

    • Reliability of sensor data during the trip
In[23]:
# Derive age first
REFERENCE_YEAR = 2025  
df_copy['age'] = REFERENCE_YEAR - df_copy['date_of_birth'].dt.year

trip_features = (
    df_copy.groupby('bookingID')
    .agg(
        trip_duration=('second', lambda x: x.max() - x.min()),

2.2 Comparing means by class + percent differences

Goal: Identify features that discriminate between safe/dangerous

Comparing means answers:

  • Do dangerous trips have higher average speed?

  • Do they brake harder or more frequently?

  • Are they more erratic on average?

If the mean of a feature is:

  • Significantly higher for dangerous trips potential predictive signal

  • Very similar across classes weak predictor

In[24]:
numerical_features = [
    'trip_duration',
    'Speed_mean', 'Speed_max', 'Speed_std',
    'longitudinal_acc_std', 'longitudinal_acc_min', 'longitudinal_acc_max',
    'is_speeding_sum', 'is_harsh_braking_sum', 'is_harsh_acceleration_sum', 'is_sharp_turn_sum',
    'gyro_z_std',
    'low_gps_quality_flag_mean', 'acc_x_missing_flag_mean',
    'age'
]

comparison = trip_features.groupby('label')[numerical_features].mean(numeric_only=True)
print("Mean values by class:")
print(comparison)

print("\n% difference (dangerous vs safe):")
for feature in numerical_features:
    safe_mean = trip_features.loc[trip_features['label'] == 0, feature].mean()
    danger_mean = trip_features.loc[trip_features['label'] == 1, feature].mean()
    if safe_mean != 0 and np.isfinite(safe_mean):
        pct_diff = ((danger_mean - safe_mean) / safe_mean) * 100
        print(f"{feature}: {pct_diff:+.1f}%")
    else:
        print(f"{feature}: safe_mean0 (skip % diff)")

Trip duration outlier investigation

  • Problem is that the safe trips have such HIGH mean duration

Why It's Dangerous for ML:

  • Model will learn: "Long trip = safe, short trip = dangerous"
  • This is spurious correlation, not real driving behavior
  • Your model will fail in production when trip durations normalize

2.4 Overlaid histograms

Why overlay histograms?

Box plots summarize distributions, but histograms show shape.

Overlaid histograms allow us to inspect:

  • Distribution skewness

  • Long tails

  • Multimodality

  • Degree of overlap

What overlap tells us?

  • Low overlap feature likely useful on its own

  • High overlap feature may still work in combination

  • Identical distributions feature unlikely to help

This helps avoid over-engineering weak signals.

In[26]:
for feature in ['Speed_mean', 'Speed_std', 'is_harsh_braking_sum']:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))

    danger = trip_features.loc[trip_features['label'] == 1, feature].dropna()

    plt.hist(danger, bins=50, alpha=0.5, label='Dangerous', density=True)

Observations for both box plots and histograms

  • Distribution Overlap: As seen in the histograms for Speed_mean and Speed_std, the distributions for Safe and Dangerous trips almost entirely overlap.

  • Event Spikes: The is_harsh_braking_sum histogram shows that both classes have a high density at zero, but the "Dangerous" class has a much "longer tail," with more trips recording 5 to 20+ harsh braking events.

  • Outliers: The box plots reveal extreme outliers in Speed_mean for safe trips and is_speeding_sum for both classes, where some trips have hundreds of speeding seconds.

  • Analysis: Because the bulk of the distributions overlap, no single feature acts as a "silver bullet" to separate the classes. This confirms that a simple rule-based system will fail. We must use non-linear ML models (like Random Forest or XGBoost) that can find the interaction between these features (e.g., high gyro_z_std + high is_harsh_braking_sum).

5.2 Event clustering / gaps

Shorter gaps between events indicate:

  • Aggressive, continuous risky behaviour

  • Higher likelihood of dangerous classification

This insight motivates:

  • Burstiness features

  • Rolling-window statistics

In[31]:
def analyze_event_gaps(df_subset, event_col='is_harsh_braking'):
    """
    Average time gap between consecutive events within trips.
    Smaller average gap = more clustered/bursty events.
    """
    df_sorted = df_subset.sort_values(['bookingID', 'second']).copy()
    events = df_sorted[df_sorted[event_col] == 1].copy()
    if events.empty:
        return np.nan

    events['prev_second'] = events.groupby('bookingID')['second'].shift(1)
    events['gap'] = events['second'] - events['prev_second']
    return events['gap'].dropna().mean()

safe_df = df_copy[df_copy['label'] == 0]
danger_df = df_copy[df_copy['label'] == 1]

print("\nAverage seconds between harsh brakes:")
print(f"Safe trips: {analyze_event_gaps(safe_df, 'is_harsh_braking')}")
print(f"Dangerous trips: {analyze_event_gaps(danger_df, 'is_harsh_braking')}")

Safe trips: 201.45200907755975
Dangerous trips: 233.89334662347372

Observations

  • Duration Anomaly: Safe trips have a mean duration of 165,903 seconds, while dangerous trips average 1,169 seconds.

  • Event Gaps: The average time between harsh brakes is 201 seconds for safe trips and 233 seconds for dangerous trips.

  • Analysis: The massive duration for safe trips (equivalent to nearly 46 hours) is likely a data quality issue or a sensor that wasn't turned off. If left uncleaned, the model will "cheat" by assuming any very long trip is automatically safe. We must address this in Step 1.2 (Handling Imbalance/Cleaning).

Step 7: Leakage check

  • Goal: See whether a simple rule based on events can almost perfectly predict label.

  • If yes, be cautious with any hand-crafted risk score features.

Why leakage analysis is critical?

Leakage occurs when the model learns:

  • Information derived from the label

  • Rules that mirror label creation logic

This leads to:

  • Inflated evaluation scores

  • Poor real-world performance

In[33]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Simple proxy score (NOT a final feature)
trip_features['proxy_risk_score'] = (
    2*trip_features['is_speeding_sum'] +
    2*trip_features['is_harsh_braking_sum'] +
    2*trip_features['is_harsh_acceleration_sum'] +
    2*trip_features['is_sharp_turn_sum']
)

corr_val = trip_features['proxy_risk_score'].corr(trip_features['label'])
print(f"Correlation proxy_risk_score vs label: {corr_val:.3f}")

for threshold in [5, 10, 20, 30, 50]:
    predicted = (trip_features['proxy_risk_score'] > threshold).astype(int)
    acc = accuracy_score(trip_features['label'], predicted)
    print(f"Threshold {threshold}: Accuracy = {acc:.3f}")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.scatter(trip_features['proxy_risk_score'], trip_features['label'], alpha=0.3)
plt.xlabel('Proxy Risk Score (EDA-only)')
plt.ylabel('Label (0=Safe, 1=Dangerous)')
plt.title('Proxy Risk Score vs Label (Leakage/Proxy Check)')
plt.show()

Correlation proxy_risk_score vs label: 0.156
Threshold 5: Accuracy = 0.492
Threshold 10: Accuracy = 0.588
Threshold 20: Accuracy = 0.649
Threshold 30: Accuracy = 0.678
Threshold 50: Accuracy = 0.705

Observations

  • Proxy Performance: The proxy_risk_score only reaches 70.5% accuracy at its best threshold.

  • Baseline Comparison: This is lower than the baseline accuracy of 75.03%.

  • Analysis: This proves there is no data leakage from a simple "sum of bad events" logic. If the proxy score had 99% accuracy, it would mean the label was likely generated by a simple formula we already know. Since it performs poorly, it justifies the use of complex ML to find the true underlying patterns of dangerous driving.

EDA summary

1. Problem Definition

  • Task type: Supervised binary classification

    • label = 0 Normal/Safe trip

    • label = 1 Dangerous trip

  • Why not time-series forecasting?

    • We are not predicting future sensor values. We use time ordering only to extract behaviour features (volatility, harsh events, turning patterns), then predict trip safety.

2. Class Distribution (Target Analysis)

  • Dataset is moderately imbalanced: about 75% Safe / 25% Dangerous ( 3:1).

  • Baseline accuracy 75% if we always predict Safe.

  • Implication: Accuracy alone can be misleading. We should evaluate with metrics like Recall / F1 for Dangerous trips and consider imbalance handling (class weights / SMOTE) later.

3. Key Behavioural Differences Between Safe vs Dangerous Trips Strongest signal: Turning / steering volatility

  • Dangerous trips show much higher steering volatility, especially:

    • gyro_z_std is ~+58.6% higher in dangerous trips.

    • is_sharp_turn_sum and gyro_z_std appear among the top correlated predictors.

  • Interpretation: Dangerous driving here is strongly associated with frequent sharp turns / erratic steering.

Aggressive manoeuvres are more frequent

Dangerous trips show higher extreme event counts:

  • Harsh braking: ~+40.9%

  • Harsh acceleration: ~+36.8%

  • Speeding events: ~+42.3%

Speed paradox

  • Dangerous trips have lower mean speed (~-8.4%) but higher acceleration intensity (longitudinal_acc_max).

  • Interpretation: Danger appears driven by stop-and-go aggression and sharp steering (likely urban conditions), not sustained high-speed cruising.

4. Driver and Demographic Findings

Driver behaviour is situational

  • Driver danger rates form a spread around ~25%, with no driver being 0% or 100% dangerous.

  • Conclusion: Danger depends on trip context, not simply bad drivers.

Age is weak (in this dataset)

  • Danger rates across age groups are very similar (e.g., 3550 24.7% vs 50+ 25.3%).

  • Conclusion: Age likely provides limited predictive power (may be kept as a minor feature or dropped later after model validation).

5. Feature Relationships / Redundancy

  • No extremely high feature-feature correlations (no pairs with |r| > 0.9).

  • Good news: low redundancy reduces instability in feature importance and reduces risk of duplicate signals.

6. Data Quality Findings (Important)

Trip duration anomaly (major artefact)

  • Safe trips show unrealistically huge durations (mean ~46 hours; max values are impossible).

  • Extreme long trips are almost all labelled Safe, creating a spurious shortcut:

    • model may learn very long trip safe (not true driving behaviour)

  • Action later in preprocessing: filter/cap trips to a reasonable duration range to avoid the model learning dataset artefacts.

Bearing=0 interpretation confirmed

  • Only a small fraction of Bearing=0 occurs when Speed > 1 m/s.

  • Conclusion: Bearing=0 is mostly consistent with stationary periods, not missing data.

acceleration_x missingness is not biased

  • Missing rate is low (~2.6%) and nearly identical across classes.

  • No trips have extreme missingness.

  • Conclusion: Our approach (acceleration_x_filled + acc_x_missing_flag) is safe and wont introduce class bias.

GPS quality behaves unexpectedly

  • GPS quality patterns suggest it may be a confounder (poor GPS may mask events).

  • Conclusion: keep GPS quality features/flags so the model can account for sensor reliability.

7. Leakage / Proxy Check

  • Hand-crafted proxy score achieved ~70.5%, which is below the 75% baseline.

  • Conclusion: label is not trivially recoverable via simple thresholds supports using ML models to capture complex interactions.
